### Description

I have a use case where I need to completely tear down my Angular application then bootstrap it again as if Angular was never bootstrapped there in the first place (I know it's wacky).

It appears the `.destroy()` method leaves behind the providers for subsequent Angular initializations to use.

If I have an application that has an external counter and dependency injects the value of the counter into the application, tearing down and bootstrapping the whole application whenever there is a new value on the counter - consumers of that dependency will always get the first value provided - even if the instance consuming that value has been `.destroy()`ed

```typescript
let i: number = 0;
let ngRef: NgModuleRef | undefined

setInterval(async () => {
  i++;

  if (ngRef) {
    ngRef.destroy();
    ngRef = undefined;
  }

  document.body.appendChild(document.createElement('app-root'))

  const staticProviders: StaticProvider[] = [
    { provide: 'setInterval', useValue: i },
  ]

  ngRef = await platformBrowserDynamic(staticProviders)
    .bootstrapModule(AppModule);
}, 5000);
```

```typescript
@Component({
  selector: 'my-app',
  template: '<p>Count: {{ count }}</p>', // I expect this to count "1", "2", "3"... but it will always render "1" no matter the real value
})
export class AppComponent {
  constructor(@Inject('setInterval') public count: number) {}
}
```

